I truely do not know how many were prosecuted for violation of the selective service laws, nor do I know how these numbers could be obtained.  I suspect that you may be right that it wasn't many.  The only one on this site who claimed that he spent two years of &quot;bed pan service&quot; for avoiding the draft, lost all credibility, so I couldn't even begin to guess.<br><br>
One thing did come to mind after my last posting, though.  <br>
If only one fifth of those qualified for amnesty applied, they truely must not have cared for their country enough to return.  Does this make a blanket statement that the claims by some that they &quot;sacrificed&quot; by protesting/demonstrating, publicly evading the draft as a form of protest, burning draft cards, for the good of the soldiers, the potential draftees, the Vietnamese people, instead of their own self interest/preservation?  That their motives were not as altruistic as claimed?
